[src:sharp-p/matrix-permanent] In linear algebra, the **permanent** of a square matrix is a function of the matrix similar to the determinant.
[src:sharp-p/matrix-permanent] The permanent, as well as the determinant, is a polynomial in the entries of the matrix.
[src:sharp-p/matrix-permanent] Both are special cases of a more general function of a matrix called the immanant.
[src:sharp-p/matrix-permanent] The sum here extends over all elements *σ* of the symmetric group *S**n*; i.e., over all permutations of the numbers 1, 2, ..., *n*.
[src:sharp-p/matrix-permanent] The definition of the permanent of *A* differs from that of the determinant of *A* in that the signatures of the permutations are not taken into account.
[src:sharp-p/matrix-permanent] The permanent of a matrix A is denoted per *A*, perm *A*, or Per *A*, sometimes with parentheses around the argument.
[src:sharp-p/matrix-permanent] Minc uses Per(*A*) for the permanent of rectangular matrices, and per(*A*) when *A* is a square matrix.
[src:sharp-p/matrix-permanent] The word, *permanent*, originated with Cauchy in 1812 as "fonctions symétriques permanentes" for a related type of function, and was used by Muir and Metzler in the modern, more specific, sense.
[src:sharp-p/matrix-permanent] If one views the permanent as a map that takes *n* vectors as arguments, then it is a multilinear map and it is symmetric (meaning that any order of the vectors results in the same permanent).
[src:sharp-p/matrix-permanent] Laplace's expansion by minors for computing the determinant along a row, column or diagonal extends to the permanent by ignoring all signs.
[src:sharp-p/matrix-permanent] where $B_{i,j}$ is the entry of the *i*th row and the *j*th column of *B*, and ${\textstyle M_{i,j}}$ is the permanent of the submatrix obtained by removing the *i*th row and the *j*th column of *B*.
[src:sharp-p/matrix-permanent] On the other hand, the basic multiplicative property of determinants is not valid for permanents.
[src:sharp-p/matrix-permanent] Unlike the determinant, the permanent has no easy geometrical interpretation; it is mainly used in combinatorics, in treating boson Green's functions in quantum field theory, and in determining state probabilities of boson sampling systems.
[src:sharp-p/matrix-permanent] However, it has two graph-theoretic interpretations: as the sum of weights of cycle covers of a directed graph, and as the sum of weights of perfect matchings in a bipartite graph.
[src:sharp-p/matrix-permanent] The permanent arises naturally in the study of the symmetric tensor power of Hilbert spaces.
[src:sharp-p/matrix-permanent] In particular, for a Hilbert space H , let $\vee ^{k}H$ denote the k th symmetric tensor power of H , which is the space of symmetric tensors.
[src:sharp-p/matrix-permanent] Note in particular that $\vee ^{k}H$ is spanned by the symmetric products of elements in H .
[src:sharp-p/matrix-permanent] Any square matrix $A=(a_{ij})_{i,j=1}^{n}$ can be viewed as the adjacency matrix of a weighted directed graph on vertex set $V=\{1,2,\dots ,n\}$ , with $a_{ij}$ representing the weight of the arc from vertex *i* to vertex *j*.
[src:sharp-p/matrix-permanent] A cycle cover of a weighted directed graph is a collection of vertex-disjoint directed cycles in the digraph that covers all vertices in the graph.
[src:sharp-p/matrix-permanent] Thus, each vertex *i* in the digraph has a unique "successor" $\sigma (i)$ in the cycle cover, and so $\sigma$ represents a permutation on *V*.
[src:sharp-p/matrix-permanent] Conversely, any permutation $\sigma$ on *V* corresponds to a cycle cover with arcs from each vertex *i* to vertex $\sigma (i)$ .
[src:sharp-p/matrix-permanent] A square matrix $A=(a_{ij})$ can also be viewed as the adjacency matrix of a bipartite graph which has vertices $x_{1},x_{2},\dots ,x_{n}$ on one side and $y_{1},y_{2},\dots ,y_{n}$ on the other side, with $a_{ij}$ representing the weight of the edge from vertex $x_{i}$ to vertex $y_{j}$ .
[src:sharp-p/matrix-permanent] The answers to many counting questions can be computed as permanents of matrices that only have 0 and 1 as entries.
[src:sharp-p/matrix-permanent] Let Ω(*n*, *k*) be the class of all (0, 1)-matrices of order *n* with each row and column sum equal to *k*.
[src:sharp-p/matrix-permanent] Every matrix *A* in this class has perm(*A*) > 0.
[src:sharp-p/matrix-permanent] The incidence matrices every finite projective plane is in the class Ω(*n*2 + *n* + 1, *n* + 1) for some integer *n* > 1.
[src:sharp-p/matrix-permanent] The permanents corresponding to the smallest projective planes have been calculated.
[src:sharp-p/matrix-permanent] Let *Z* be the incidence matrix of the projective plane with *n* = 2, the Fano plane.
[src:sharp-p/matrix-permanent] Remarkably, perm(*Z*) = 24 = |det (*Z*)|, the absolute value of the determinant of *Z*.
[src:sharp-p/matrix-permanent] Permanents can also be used to calculate the number of permutations with restricted (prohibited) positions.
[src:sharp-p/matrix-permanent] Then perm(*A*) is equal to the number of permutations of the *n*-set that satisfy all the restrictions.
[src:sharp-p/matrix-permanent] For an *n*×*n* (0, 1)-matrix, the permanent may be equivalently described as the number of ways of placing *n* mutually non-attacking rooks on the *n*×*n* chessboard so that no rook is at a position where the matrix has a 0 entry.
[src:sharp-p/matrix-permanent] The Bregman–Minc inequality, conjectured by H.
[src:sharp-p/matrix-permanent] Brégman in 1973, gives an upper bound for the permanent of an *n* × *n* (0, 1)-matrix.
[src:sharp-p/matrix-permanent] In 1926, Van der Waerden conjectured that the minimum permanent among all *n* × *n* doubly stochastic matrices is *n*!/*n**n*, achieved by the matrix for which all entries are equal to 1/*n*.
[src:sharp-p/matrix-permanent] Proofs of this conjecture were published in 1980 by B.
[src:sharp-p/matrix-permanent] Egorychev's proof is an application of the Alexandrov–Fenchel inequality.
[src:sharp-p/matrix-permanent] For this work, Egorychev and Falikman won the Fulkerson Prize in 1982.
[src:sharp-p/matrix-permanent] The naïve approach, using the definition, of computing permanents is computationally infeasible even for relatively small matrices.
[src:sharp-p/matrix-permanent] One of the fastest known algorithms is due to H.
[src:sharp-p/matrix-permanent] Ryser's method is based on an inclusion–exclusion formula that can be given as follows: Let $A_{k}$ be obtained from *A* by deleting *k* columns, let $P(A_{k})$ be the product of the row-sums of $A_{k}$ , and let $\Sigma _{k}$ be the sum of the values of $P(A_{k})$ over all possible $A_{k}$ .
[src:sharp-p/matrix-permanent] The permanent is believed to be more difficult to compute than the determinant.
[src:sharp-p/matrix-permanent] While the determinant can be computed in polynomial time by Gaussian elimination, Gaussian elimination cannot be used to compute the permanent.
[src:sharp-p/matrix-permanent] Moreover, computing the permanent of a (0,1)-matrix is #P-complete.
[src:sharp-p/matrix-permanent] Thus, if the permanent can be computed in polynomial time by any method, then **FP = #P**, which is an even stronger statement than P = NP.
[src:sharp-p/matrix-permanent] When the entries of *A* are nonnegative, however, the permanent can be computed approximately in probabilistic polynomial time, up to an error of $\varepsilon M$ , where M is the value of the permanent and $\varepsilon >0$ is arbitrary.
[src:sharp-p/matrix-permanent] The permanent of a certain set of positive semidefinite matrices is NP-hard to approximate within any subexponential factor.
[src:sharp-p/matrix-permanent] If further conditions on the spectrum are imposed, the permanent can be approximated in probabilistic polynomial time: the best achievable error of this approximation is $\varepsilon {\sqrt {M}}$ ( M is again the value of the permanent).
[src:sharp-p/matrix-permanent] The hardness in these instances is closely linked with difficulty of simulating boson sampling experiments.
[src:sharp-p/matrix-permanent] Another way to view permanents is via multivariate generating functions.
[src:sharp-p/matrix-permanent] Let $A=(a_{ij})$ be a square matrix of order *n*.
[src:sharp-p/matrix-permanent] The permanent function can be generalized to apply to non-square matrices.
[src:sharp-p/matrix-permanent] Indeed, several authors make this the definition of a permanent and consider the restriction to square matrices a special case.
[src:sharp-p/matrix-permanent] Ryser's computational result for permanents also generalizes.
[src:sharp-p/matrix-permanent] If *A* is an *m* × *n* matrix with *m* ≤ *n*, let $A_{k}$ be obtained from *A* by deleting *k* columns, let $P(A_{k})$ be the product of the row-sums of $A_{k}$ , and let $\sigma _{k}$ be the sum of the values of $P(A_{k})$ over all possible $A_{k}$ .
[src:sharp-p/matrix-permanent] The generalization of the definition of a permanent to non-square matrices allows the concept to be used in a more natural way in some applications.
[src:sharp-p/matrix-permanent] The incidence matrix of this collection of subsets is an *m* × *n* (0,1)-matrix *A*.
[src:sharp-p/matrix-permanent] The number of systems of distinct representatives (SDR's) of this collection is perm(*A*).
[src:sharp-p/p-complete] The **#P-complete** problems (pronounced "sharp P complete", "number P complete", or "hash P complete") form a complexity class in computational complexity theory.
[src:sharp-p/p-complete] These are all necessarily members of the class #P as well.
[src:sharp-p/p-complete] As a non-example, consider the case of counting solutions to a 1-satisfiability problem: a series of variables that are each individually constrained, but have no relationships with each other.
[src:sharp-p/p-complete] The solutions can be efficiently counted, by multiplying the number of options for each variable in isolation.
[src:sharp-p/p-complete] Thus, this problem is in #P, but cannot be #P-complete unless #P=FP.
[src:sharp-p/p-complete] This would be surprising, as it would imply that P=NP=PH.
[src:sharp-p/p-complete] Some #P-complete problems correspond to easy (polynomial time) problems.
[src:sharp-p/p-complete] Determining the satisfiability of a Boolean formula in disjunctive normal form is easy: such a formula is satisfiable if and only if it contains a satisfiable conjunction (one that does not contain a variable and its negation), whereas counting the number of satisfying assignments is #P-complete.
[src:sharp-p/p-complete] Furthermore, deciding 2-satisfiability is easy compared to counting the number of satisfying assignments.
[src:sharp-p/p-complete] Topologically sorting is easy in contrast to counting the number of topological sortings.
[src:sharp-p/p-complete] A single perfect matching can be found in polynomial time, but counting all perfect matchings is #P-complete.
[src:sharp-p/p-complete] The perfect matching counting problem was the first counting problem corresponding to an easy decision problem shown to be #P-complete, in a 1979 paper by Leslie Valiant that also defined the class #P and the #P-complete problems for the first time.
[src:sharp-p/p-complete] There are probabilistic algorithms that return good approximations to some #P-complete problems with high probability.
[src:sharp-p/p-complete] This is one of the demonstrations of the power of probabilistic algorithms.
[src:sharp-p/p] In computational complexity theory, the complexity class **#P** (pronounced "sharp P" or, sometimes "number P" or "hash P") is the set of the counting problems associated with the decision problems in the set **NP**.
[src:sharp-p/p] More formally, **#P** is the class of function problems of the form "compute *f*(*x*)", where *f* is the number of accepting paths of a nondeterministic Turing machine running in polynomial time.
[src:sharp-p/p] Unlike most well-known complexity classes, it is not a class of decision problems but a class of function problems.
[src:sharp-p/p] The most difficult, representative problems of this class are #P-complete.
[src:sharp-p/p] Corresponding **#P** function problems ask "how many" rather than "are there any".
[src:sharp-p/p] Clearly, a **#P** problem must be at least as hard as the corresponding **NP** problem.
[src:sharp-p/p] If it's easy to count answers, then it must be easy to tell whether there are any answers—just count them and see whether the count is greater than zero.
[src:sharp-p/p] Some of these problems, such as root counting, are easy enough to be in FP, while others are #P-complete.
[src:sharp-p/p] One consequence of Toda's theorem is that a polynomial-time machine with a **#P** oracle (**P****#P**) can solve all problems in **PH**, the entire polynomial hierarchy.
[src:sharp-p/p] In fact, the polynomial-time machine only needs to make one **#P** query to solve any problem in **PH**.
[src:sharp-p/p] This is an indication of the extreme difficulty of solving **#P**-complete problems exactly.
[src:sharp-p/p] Surprisingly, some **#P** problems that are believed to be difficult correspond to easy (for example linear-time) **P** problems.
[src:sharp-p/p] For more information on this, see #P-complete.
[src:sharp-p/p] The closest decision problem class to **#P** is **PP**, which asks whether a majority (more than half) of the computation paths accept.
[src:sharp-p/p] This finds the most significant bit in the **#P** problem answer.
[src:sharp-p/p] The decision problem class **⊕P** (pronounced "Parity-P") instead asks for the least significant bit of the **#P** answer.
[src:sharp-p/p] equals the size of the set containing all of the polynomial-size certificates).
[src:sharp-p/p] The complexity class **#P** was first defined by Leslie Valiant in a 1979 article on the computation of the permanent of a square matrix, in which he proved that permanent is #P-complete.
[src:sharp-p/p] Larry Stockmeyer has proved that for every #P problem P there exists a randomized algorithm using an oracle for SAT, which given an instance a of P and $\epsilon >0$ returns with high probability a number x such that $(1-\epsilon )P(a)\leq x\leq (1+\epsilon )P(a)$ .
[src:sharp-p/p] The runtime of the algorithm is polynomial in a and $1/\epsilon$ .
[src:sharp-p/p] The algorithm is based on the leftover hash lemma.
[src:sharp-p/sharp-sat] In computer science, the **Sharp Satisfiability Problem** (sometimes called **Sharp-SAT**, **#SAT** or **model counting**) is the problem of counting the number of interpretations that satisfy a given Boolean formula, introduced by Valiant in 1979.
[src:sharp-p/sharp-sat] In other words, it asks in how many ways the variables of a given Boolean formula can be consistently replaced by the values TRUE or FALSE in such a way that the formula evaluates to TRUE.
[src:sharp-p/sharp-sat] We know that A can be solved using a Non-deterministic Turing Machine M.
[src:sharp-p/sharp-sat] On the other hand, from the proof for Cook-Levin Theorem, we know that we can reduce M to a boolean formula F.
[src:sharp-p/sharp-sat] Now, each valid assignment of F corresponds to a unique acceptable path in M, and vice versa.
[src:sharp-p/sharp-sat] However, each acceptable path taken by M represents a solution to A.
[src:sharp-p/sharp-sat] In other words, there is a bijection between the valid assignments of F and the solutions to A.
[src:sharp-p/sharp-sat] So, the reduction used in the proof for Cook-Levin Theorem is parsimonious.
[src:sharp-p/sharp-sat] Counting solutions is intractable (#P-complete) in many special cases for which satisfiability is tractable (in P), as well as when satisfiability is intractable (NP-complete).
[src:sharp-p/sharp-sat] One can show that any formula in SAT can be rewritten as a formula in 3-CNF form preserving the number of satisfying assignments.
[src:sharp-p/sharp-sat] Hence, #SAT and #3SAT are counting equivalent and #3SAT is #P-complete as well.
[src:sharp-p/sharp-sat] Even though 2SAT (deciding whether a 2CNF formula has a solution) is polynomial, counting the number of solutions is #P-complete.
[src:sharp-p/sharp-sat] The #P-completeness already in the monotone case, i.e., when there are no negations (#MONOTONE-2-CNF).
[src:sharp-p/sharp-sat] Similarly, even though Horn-satisfiability is polynomial, counting the number of solutions is #P-complete.
[src:sharp-p/sharp-sat] This result follows from a general dichotomy characterizing which SAT-like problems are #P-complete.
[src:sharp-p/sharp-sat] This is the counting version of Planar 3SAT.
[src:sharp-p/sharp-sat] The hardness reduction from 3SAT to Planar 3SAT given by Lichtenstein is parsimonious.
[src:sharp-p/sharp-sat] This implies that Planar #3SAT is #P-complete.
[src:sharp-p/sharp-sat] This is the counting version of Planar Monotone Rectilinear 3SAT.
[src:sharp-p/sharp-sat] The NP-hardness reduction given by de Berg & Khosravi is parsimonious.
[src:sharp-p/sharp-sat] Therefore, this problem is #P-complete as well.
[src:sharp-p/sharp-sat] Intractability even holds in the case known as #PP2DNF, where the variables are partitioned into two sets, with each clause containing one variable from each set.
[src:sharp-p/sharp-sat] By contrast, it is possible to tractably approximate the number of solutions of a disjunctive normal form formula using the Karp-Luby algorithm, which is an FPRAS for this problem.
[src:sharp-p/sharp-sat] The variant of SAT corresponding to affine relations in the sense of Schaefer's dichotomy theorem, i.e., where clauses amount to equations modulo 2 with the XOR operator, is the only SAT variant for which the #SAT problem can be solved in polynomial time.
[src:sharp-p/sharp-sat] If the instances to SAT are restricted using graph parameters, the #SAT problem can become tractable.
[src:sharp-p/sharp-sat] For instance, #SAT on SAT instances whose treewidth is bounded by a constant can be performed in polynomial time.
[src:sharp-p/sharp-sat] Here, the treewidth can be the primal treewidth, dual treewidth, or incidence treewidth of the hypergraph associated to the SAT formula, whose vertices are the variables and where each clause is represented as a hyperedge.
[src:sharp-p/sharp-sat] Model counting is tractable (solvable in polynomial time) for (ordered) BDDs and for some circuit formalisms studied in knowledge compilation, such as d-DNNFs.
[src:sharp-p/sharp-sat] Weighted model counting (WMC) generalizes #SAT by computing a linear combination of the models instead of just counting the models.
[src:sharp-p/sharp-sat] In the literal-weighted variant of WMC, each literal gets assigned a weight, such that ${\text{WMC}}(\phi ;w)=\sum _{M\models \phi }\prod _{l\in M}w(l)$ .
[src:sharp-p/sharp-sat] WMC is used for probabilistic inference, as probabilistic queries over discrete random variables such as in Bayesian networks can be reduced to WMC.
[src:sharp-p/sharp-sat] Algebraic model counting further generalizes #SAT and WMC over arbitrary commutative semirings.
